article.description:
Jocelyn Penn had 28 points and eight
rebounds and No. 18 South Carolina beat Alcorn State 96-52 on
Sunday.
article.headline: Gamecocks' transition game too much for  Alcorn State
article.linkText: Penn's stellar season continues in South Carolina win
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) --   South Carolina coach Susan Walvius has
seen it so many times -- Jocelyn Penn sprints into the open court
and gets an easy layup in transition.

	   That helps to explain why she's one of the nation's leading
scorers at 27 points a game.

	   "Jocelyn has shown our team, through her leadership by example,
that if you get out and run the floor on made baskets, good things
will happen to you," Walvius said.

	   Penn scored 28 points, most in transition, and grabbed eight
rebounds as No. 18 South Carolina beat Alcorn State 96-52 on
Sunday.

	   Penn isn't the only one leading the Gamecocks' run-and-gun
system. South Carolina had five players score in double figures and
scored 30 points off turnovers and 52 points in the paint.

	   "We as a team our doing a better job in our transition game,"
Walvius said. "When we do that, we get easy baskets."

	   Penn sparked an early 11-0 run with five points as the Gamecocks
(10-1) went up 17-6 with 15:17 left in the first half. During the
run, South Carolina converted two of its 10 first-half steals into
easy layups.

	   Penn continued her record-setting season Sunday. She grabbed an
offensive rebound on Petra Ujhelyi's missed free throw and her
putback gave her 1,501 career points. With the basket, the senior
became one of only four players in school history to score more
than 1,500 points, grab 500 rebounds and have more than 200 steals.

	   "All I can say is it's just an honor,"  Penn said. "It just
shows how hard I've worked and how hard my teammates work to get me
the ball."

	   Ciocan had 14 points and eight assists, while Ujhelyi scored 13
points and Tonisha Reese added a career-high 13 for the Gamecocks.

	   Danielle Tipton scored 16 points for the Braves (6-4) and
Keairra Levy added 12.

	   Alcorn State coach Shirley Walker said she didn't recognize her
team Sunday. The usually up-tempo team slowed early and couldn't
keep up with the Gamecocks' pace, especially Penn.

	   Walker changed the defense to a matchup zone to try to slow
Penn, but it didn't work.

	   "We weren't able to contain her at all," Walker said. "She's
one of the best ball players we have played against this season."

	   South Carolina shot 64.5 (20-for-31) from the field in the first
half and had eight fewer turnovers. The Gamecocks led 32-14 on Olga
Gritsaeva's basket with 6:34 remaining and tied their largest lead
of the half -- 18 points -- on Reese's short jumper as time expired.

	   Walvius said it was a good game for role players like Reese.

	   "We call Tonisha Reese 'instant-offense.' She is really a
tremendous offensive player," Walvius said. "She can shoot off
the dribble, she can get to the rim. She's small but she has no
problem shooting over big players."

	   South Carolina began the second half like it ended the first.
Penn's nine points led a 15-6 run, and Ciocan's 3 with 13:42 left
put the Gamecocks up 68-30. They would lead by as many as 44
points.

	   Alcorn State hung around in the first half shooting 60 percent
(6-of-10) from 3-point range. Tipton hit all four of her 3-point
attempts and Keairra Levy added two.

	   "The team did a nice job of making some adjustments at halftime
and we came out and contained the two leading scorers," Walvius
said.
